the test counted the number of rows in a grid immediately after closing a modal(that deleted an element). Therefore the test would fail if the grid wasn't updated in between the modal closing and skywalker counting the number of rows. I added a waitForAjax() that allows the fetch requests to complete before counting the updated number of rows. Also, i made the selector for table rows more specific so ensure we don't count rows in page-cache div

The chart was not showing up since it was configured to show avg risk scores of only parent assets and we didn't have any parent assets with a non-empty risk score. The fix was to re-define a field on BaseAsset called avgRiskScore as a stored calc equal to the average of latest risk scores of all the children of that {@link BaseAsset}. For assets with no children it is 0.

Cause: mills second isn't persisted in the timestamp, so descending(timestamp) won't sort two records correctly. Solution: add sleep one second in the test.

Because the millisecond part of the timestamp isn't persisted in the database, if two events happen in the same second, the database won't be able to pick up the latest one since both have the exact same timestamp.

There is two parts to this fix. The first part is that in our TestApi teardown function, Series header types are cleaned up first before the measurements are removed. the second part is a bug found on platform and that needs to be fixed before this ticket can be closed. (PLAT-14741). The main problem on the platform is that the state object for normalization was not being updated to reflect that the series header is no longer there. That logic has been fixed so that the state is updated before the maximum retries is reached. Apps code can be fixed, but server needs to be updated to the version containing fix before this can be closed.

The test failed because this.endDate is 2018-11-01, so end is 2018-10-01, start is 2018-04-01. When end is at the beginning of a month, metric is evaluated to the end of the previous month, so the metric will be evaluated from April to September, a total of 6 months. When end is at the end of a month, metric is evaluated to the end of that month. If end is 2018-10-02, start is 2018-04-02, metric will be evaluated from April to October, a total of 7 months. I changed end to make sure it is always the end of the month, so the interval will always be 7 months.

c3 tester is used in the apps pipeline and it is using the default batch size of 75. When batch size is low, multiple tests are running simultaneously, and due to limited shared computing resources, tests are timing out.

The problem is with the two lines of code below collection.load(); collection.whenLoaded(function() { self.renderSeries.apply(self, arguments); }); The whenLoaded event is after collection.load(). It is possible the collection is loaded before whenLoaded is added. When that scenario happens, the renderSeries function is not called. The solution is to reverse the order of those two lines.
